Separate Name and Type Analysis: 

Even if you do some trivial checks in the parser (e.g. enter every
declared name into the symbol table immediately), plan to run a full name-resolution and type-check 
pass on the AST afterward. For example, you might perform a declaration collection pass first (to record
all symbols in each scope) and then a type-checking pass. This follows traditional compiler design 
(and even educational projects). It also simplifies handling recursive declarations and forward references.

Use a Well-Structured AST and Symbol Table:

Design an AST node hierarchy that cleanly separates untyped syntax from typed semantic information. 
After parsing, annotate AST nodes with semantic facts (resolved variable references, inferred types, closure
environments). Use a symbol table abstraction that supports nested scopes. Many front ends (including Clang) 
maintain separate “source” vs “semantic” views of symbols at minimum, be clear when you have multiple 
declarations of the same name (overloads) versus a single resolved entity.

Support Incremental Checks:

For rapid feedback (and potential IDE integration), the hybrid approach of doing some checks early can be helpful.
For instance, you can report undefined-variable errors immediately when parsing statements, even if full type-checking
of the expression is delayed. Likewise, you might check function signatures (e.g. return types match declared types) 
as soon as the function is parsed, before analyzing the body. These staged checks can prevent the compiler from flooding 
the user with errors that are consequences of a single mistake.


Leverage LLVMs Type System:

Since the target is LLVM IR, use the semantic pass to map your language types to LLVM types cleanly. LLVM requires 
concrete types (no overloading or type inference in IR), so all generic type logic must be resolved beforehand. 
For closures, implement a transformation that turns a closure AST node into an explicit struct and function, then 
generate LLVM IR for those constructs. In other words, do the “closure conversion” during semantics, not in codegen. 
Similarly, resolve overloaded functions to unique LLVM function names (mangling) during semantic analysis.


Rigorous Error Reporting:

Especially for a security language, unambiguous errors are crucial. Collect error information in the semantic pass 
and present them consistently. If you defer checks to the separate pass, you can gather multiple errors per node 
(e.g. type mismatches in several places) and present a single coherent message. Use the full-module context to avoid
spurious errors.

Security Annotations in the AST:

If the language has security annotations (e.g. “@safe”, “@trusted”, or taint qualifiers), enforce these in semantic analysis.
For example, check that a function marked @safe cannot perform disallowed casts or system calls. Tag AST nodes with security
metadata so that codegen can emit instrumentation (stack guards, encryption) later. Designing the semantic phase to understand
these features will harden the language effectively.